    "author_association": "NONE",
    "body": "### Problem\n\nIf a `vim.pack.add` call fails to install some plugins, the plugins will be removed from the lockfile. Next run of `vim.pack.add` will still install the plguins as declared in config, but since the entries are not in lockfile they will be reset to the latest version.\n\n### Steps to reproduce\n\nWith config:\n```lua\n-- init.lua\nvim.pack.add({\n  \"https://github.com/nvim-mini/mini.align\",\n  \"https://github.com/nvim-mini/mini.misc\",\n})\n-- or any numbers of any plugins\n```\nAnd lockfile\n```json\n{\n  \"plugins\": {\n    \"mini.align\": {\n      \"rev\": \"4d45e0e4f1fd8baefb6ae52a44659704fe7ebe8b\",\n      \"src\": \"https://github.com/nvim-mini/mini.align\"\n    },\n    \"mini.misc\": {\n      \"rev\": \"de8947231c29012271722651aa07f6749c41d1ed\",\n      \"src\": \"https://github.com/nvim-mini/mini.misc\"\n    }\n  }\n}\n```\nRun Neovim without network and confirm to install the plugins.\nThe lockfile will now be empty.\n\n### Expected behavior\n\nThe lockfile should retain the plugins that failed to install to make sure the correct versions are installed on next invocation.\n\n`vim.pack.add` should not remove any entries from lockfile and keep the config reproducible.\n\n### Nvim version (nvim -v)\n\n0.12.0\n\n### Vim (not Nvim) behaves the same?\n\nno\n\n### Operating system/version\n\nTermux, Android 14; MacOS 26\n\n### Terminal name/version\n\nTermux; WezTerm\n\n### $TERM environment variable\n\nxterm-256color\n\n### Installation\n\nTermux Packages; Nixpkgs Unstable",
    "closed_at": null,
    "closed_by": null,
    "comment_data": [
        {
            "author_association": "MEMBER",
            "body": "Thanks for the issue!\n\nMy current understanding that this fits in both [documented behavior](https://github.com/neovim/neovim/blob/f2cdf73afc7307fc65ab21134bcc4549ac34b2d4/runtime/doc/pack.txt#L225-L234) and what I'd expect to happen. Both of these come from the idea of \"lockfile describes the latest state of all managed plugins\". As in:\n\n- If a plugin was not installed (either due to unexpected error or after intentional not confirmation), then it is not managed by `vim.pack` and should not have entry in the lockfile.\n- In case there are errors during install, they are explicitly shown for user to know that something went wrong and some extra action is required. In this case, ensure that the lockfile is at the state you'd expect and try again. Similar to how [reverting from the update](https://github.com/neovim/neovim/blob/f2cdf73afc7307fc65ab21134bcc4549ac34b2d4/runtime/doc/pack.txt#L320-L328) works, as these two cases look similar: there was an unintended effect (plugin's state is not as they expect; be it \"different revision\" or \"missing from disk entirely\") of the user action which they want to revert.\n\n> `vim.pack.add` should not remove any entries from lockfile and keep the config reproducible.\n\nThe config is assumed to be reproducible in combination with tracking lockfile in the VCS. And this is shown in the [\"Synchronize config across machines\"](https://github.com/neovim/neovim/blob/f2cdf73afc7307fc65ab21134bcc4549ac34b2d4/runtime/doc/pack.txt#L334-L342) section.\n\nAt the moment, I think the best course of action would be to document this edge case in that example workflow. However, I'll take my time to explore how other package/plugin managers deal with this and if it is feasible to do in the `vim.pack` (initial skip through code resulted into \"not exactly easy\" estimation).",
